" alt=3D"Stocking 5 gallon" width=3D"667" height=3D"315"><figcaption id=3D"=
caption-attachment-45664" class=3D"wp-caption-text">Stocking 5 gallon</figc=
aption></figure>
<p>The heavy stocking columns for the ten and five gallon aquariums have be=
en crossed out for a reason. The filters for small tanks are always very sm=
all cartridge or air operated sponge filters. These filters are just totall=
y inadequate to support heavy stocking.&nbsp; So small aquariums should not=
 be heavily stocked. If one puts something like a very small canister filte=
r on a ten gallon, one can think about heavy stocking. But I=E2=80=99ve nev=
er seen that done.</p>
<figure id=3D"attachment_53330" aria-describedby=3D"caption-attachment-5333=
0" style=3D"width: 750px" class=3D"wp-caption alignnone"><img loading=3D"la=
zy" decoding=3D"async" class=3D"wp-image-53330" src=3D"https://aquariumscie=
nce.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/Nimbochromis-fuscotaeniatus-00.jpg" alt=
=3D"Nimbochromis fuscotaeniatus" width=3D"750" height=3D"346"><figcaption i=
d=3D"caption-attachment-53330" class=3D"wp-caption-text">Nimbochromis fusco=
taeniatus</figcaption></figure>
<p>To get a good number with mixed sizes just takes some common sense appro=
ximating. Start with the largest fish and work your way down in size. Say y=
ou have a 50 gallon and want to stock at the maximum recommended level.</p>
<p>Say you want 10 three inch fish. The 10 three inch fish is very roughly =
about half the quotas for =E2=80=9CMaximum recommended=E2=80=9D. That leave=
s 50% which could be 23 two inch fish (50% of 47). But lets say its ten thr=
ee inch (roughly 50%) and 12 two inch (roughly 25% of 47). Then you would h=
ave room for one fourth (25%) of the 315 in one inch fish or about 80 one i=
nch fish. So it is 10 three inch, 12 two inch and 80 one inch fish in a fif=
ty gallon.</p>
<p>That is all very rough. A more thorough analysis involves using the weig=
ht of the fish and gets all complicated totally unnecessarily. The easy way=
 to do it is just to add small numbers of fish till the water turns =E2=80=
=9Cdull=E2=80=9D. Then stop adding till the water becomes crystal clear. Th=
en add more fish. Easy.</p>
<figure id=3D"attachment_42650" aria-describedby=3D"caption-attachment-4265=
0" style=3D"width: 847px" class=3D"wp-caption alignnone"><img loading=3D"la=
zy" decoding=3D"async" class=3D"size-full wp-image-42650" src=3D"https://aq=
uariumscience.org/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nimbochromis-venustus10.jpg" a=
lt=3D"Nimbochromis venustus" width=3D"847" height=3D"493"><figcaption id=3D=
"caption-attachment-42650" class=3D"wp-caption-text">Nimbochromis venustus<=
/figcaption></figure>
<p>Now <span style=3D"font-size: inherit;">these numbers, especially the =
=E2=80=9Cheavy stocking=E2=80=9D numbers, will absolutely send some =E2=80=
=9Cfish police=E2=80=9D into absolute hysteria and get this site kicked off=
 many Facebook forums. Remember, the heavy stocking levels are only =E2=80=
=9C<strong> MY OPINIONS</strong>=E2=80=9D (not =E2=80=9Crules=E2=80=9D) bas=
ed on<strong> WELL FILTERED AQUARIUMS WHICH HAVE LARGE FILTERS WITH GOOD ME=
DIA THAT HASN=E2=80=99T BEEN FREQUENTLY CLEANED!!!!!</strong></span></p>
<p>There are ways to determine the amount of media and the amount of filtra=
tion needed for a given loading of fish. They can be found in the following=
 link:</p>
<h4 style=3D"padding-left: 40px;"><strong><a href=3D"http://aquariumscience=
.org/index.php/8-8-filter-and-media-design/">8.8. Sizing Filters and Media<=
/a></strong></h4>
<p>In the in depth articles below I give my <strong>OPINIONS</strong> on th=
e topic and the <strong>OPINIONS</strong> of others. It is all a rambling s=
et of <strong>OPINIONS</strong> so unless you want to get really bored, sto=
p right here.</p>
<figure id=3D"attachment_43195" aria-describedby=3D"caption-attachment-4319=
5" style=3D"width: 750px" class=3D"wp-caption alignnone"><img loading=3D"la=
zy" decoding=3D"async" class=3D"wp-image-43195" src=3D"https://aquariumscie=
nce.org/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Andinocara-rivalatus-Golden-Saum06.jpg" =
alt=3D"Andinocara rivalatus Golden Saum" width=3D"750" height=3D"441"><figc=
aption id=3D"caption-attachment-43195" class=3D"wp-caption-text">Andinocara=
 rivalatus Golden Saum</figcaption></figure>
<h5><strong>Stocking in Greater Depth</strong></h5>
<p>Hopefully the following links can put some common sense into this subjec=
t:</p>
<h4 style=3D"padding-left: 40px;"><a href=3D"https://aquariumscience.org/in=
dex.php/13-1-stocking-opinions/"><strong>13.1. Stocking Opinions</strong></=
a></h4>
