		<div class=3D"comment-content" itemprop=3D"text">
		=09
			<p>It perfectly captures my thoughts when I read this article. Many aqua=
rium articles from Europe and the U.S. tend to present fixed numbers for fi=
sh stocking, and anyone who keeps fish at a higher density is often critici=
zed. In Asia=E2=80=94especially Southeast Asia=E2=80=94we have a different =
approach. We usually don=E2=80=99t use sponge filters or canister filters; =
we use sumps that are as large as the main tanks. The water pumps have a ve=
ry high turnover rate, and when using moving bed media (e.g., K1), we emplo=
y strong air pumps.</p>
<p>I=E2=80=99ve seen tanks around 160 liters (about 40 gallons) that house =
more than 30 large ranchu and oranda goldfish. The water remains crystal cl=
ear, odorless, and the fish are healthy. When it comes to koi, filtration s=
ystems in Asia are often half the size of the pond itself, and some even bu=
ild filter chambers equal to two-thirds of the pond=E2=80=99s volume. That=
=E2=80=99s why seeing large koi crowded together in clean, clear water is q=
uite common here.</p>
<p>Even with discus fish=E2=80=94known for being extremely sensitive to wat=
er quality=E2=80=94Southeast Asian breeders are masters at developing new, =
colorful strains. Our discus tanks are stocked very densely, yet the fish s=
tay strong and healthy. Therefore, stocking density primarily depends on th=
e filtration system. What may seem overcrowded and risky for one person cou=
ld be perfectly fine for another. It doesn=E2=80=99t mean that the latter d=
oesn=E2=80=99t care for their fish or doesn=E2=80=99t know what they=E2=80=
=99re doing.</p>
		</div>

